The mission was considered a total failure, lasted nowhere as long as planned, etc. One week later Apollo 11 landed on the moon. The press started heavily mocking the scientists behind the Biosatellite, people laughed at their caricatures in newspapers, the program was cancelled.

Deep Moon Landing revisionism argument: In June 1969 NASA launched the "Biosatellite 3" mission where a Monkeynaut was sent into space and monitored in terms of brain activity, cardiovascular health, electrolyte balance, etc. The monkey rapidly deteriorated and ended up dead.

The media said it was a waste of taxpayer money by charlatans and looked primitive compared to what was going on at the time, but what if that was the real state of American space aviation? I.e. pretty advanced already, but still a few decades away from putting a man on the moon.

Galkovsky had a conspiracy theory that something similar happened to the dead astronauts of Soyuz 11. They were in space for 24 days and died. The evidence for a valve malfunction is dubious and lots of the documents were cover-up-y. The following Soyuz flight lasted only 2 days.

It took until Soyuz 17 multiple missions and many years later to try to fly that long again when they did 29 days. Then they quickly ramped it up to 60 and 90 days the following ones. If you only look at mission duration it looks like they overrated themselves then built back up.
